  },
  {
    "id": "page_0189-b005",
    "page_key": 189,
    "order": 5,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "Residual or skip connections are branches in the computational path, whereby the input to each network layer $f[\\bullet]$ is added back to the output (figure 11.4a). By analogy to equation 11.1, the residual network is defined as:",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0189-b006",
    "page_key": 189,
    "order": 6,
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\mathbf{h}_1 &= \\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x},\\boldsymbol{\\phi}_1] \\\\\n\\mathbf{h}_2 &= \\mathbf{h}_1+\\mathbf{f}_2[\\mathbf{h}_1,\\boldsymbol{\\phi}_2] \\\\\n\\mathbf{h}_3 &= \\mathbf{h}_2+\\mathbf{f}_3[\\mathbf{h}_2,\\boldsymbol{\\phi}_3] \\\\\n\\mathbf{y} &= \\mathbf{h}_3+\\mathbf{f}_4[\\mathbf{h}_3,\\boldsymbol{\\phi}_4]\n\\end{aligned}\\qquad (11.4)\n$$",
    "source": "codex-fusion",
    "confidence": "medium",
    "latex": "\\begin{aligned}\n\\mathbf{h}_1 &= \\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x},\\boldsymbol{\\phi}_1] \\\\\n\\mathbf{h}_2 &= \\mathbf{h}_1+\\mathbf{f}_2[\\mathbf{h}_1,\\boldsymbol{\\phi}_2] \\\\\n\\mathbf{h}_3 &= \\mathbf{h}_2+\\mathbf{f}_3[\\mathbf{h}_2,\\boldsymbol{\\phi}_3] \\\\\n\\mathbf{y} &= \\mathbf{h}_3+\\mathbf{f}_4[\\mathbf{h}_3,\\boldsymbol{\\phi}_4]\n\\end{aligned}\\qquad (11.4)"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0189-b007",
    "page_key": 189,
    "order": 7,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "where the first term on the right-hand side of each line is the residual connection. Each function $f_{k}$ learns an additive change to the current representation. It follows that their outputs must be the same size as their inputs. Each additive combination of the input and the processed output is known as a residual block or residual layer.",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0189-b008",
    "page_key": 189,
    "order": 8,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "Once more, we can write this as a single function by substituting in the expressions for the intermediate quantities $h_{k}$ :",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0189-b009",
    "page_key": 189,
    "order": 9,
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\mathbf{y} &= \\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x}] \\\\\n&\\quad +\\mathbf{f}_2\\left[\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x}]\\right] \\\\\n&\\quad +\\mathbf{f}_3\\left[\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x}]+\\mathbf{f}_2\\left[\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x}]\\right]\\right] \\\\\n&\\quad +\\mathbf{f}_4\\left[\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x}]+\\mathbf{f}_2\\left[\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x}]\\right]+\\mathbf{f}_3\\left[\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x}]+\\mathbf{f}_2\\left[\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{f}_1[\\mathbf{x}]\\right]\\right]\\right]\n\\end{aligned}\\qquad (11.5)\n$$",
    "source": "codex-fusion",
